Current implementation will copy the input Iterable three times;
1. Ordering.sortedCopy first copies the input into an ArrayList.
2. sortedCopy then calls Collections.sort, which makes a second copy of the input because it invokes the list's toArray method.
3. Finally, a third copy is made of the input when immutableSortedCopy passes the sorted ArrayList to ImmutableList.copyOf, which clones the data using toArray.

If ImmutableList exposed its construct method as package-private, a much more efficient implementation to immutableSortedCopy would be:

Object[] array = Iterables.toArray( iterable, Object.class );
Arrays.sort( array, ( Ordering ) this );
return ImmutableList.construct( array );

The newly exposed ImmutableList.construct method could be used in other guava methods where the array is guaranteed to be internally created.

