Add Iterators.whileTrue(Iterator&lt;T> iterator, Predicate&lt;T> predicate).

The returned iterator will loop while the Precondition holds. (The name could be improved but "while" is a java keyword so it can't be used).

This feature is useful for large and sorted iterators where the iterator will be accessed lazily.  So for example imagine the use case:

VeryBigData&lt;String,T> data...;
Iterator&lt;T> iterator = data.seek("start_key");

If you are going to consume the iterator immediately then you can go for the regular while/loop approach

while(iterator.hasNext()) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;T elem = iterator.next();
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;if(elem.id.equals("end_key")) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;break;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// do something
}

However, what if you are not the consumer of that iterator? Or you want to apply some additional logic and hand it off? (ie a lazy use case). Then you could use Iterators.whileTrue(...) as:

Iterator.whileTrue(iterator, Predicates.not(Predicates.equals("end_key"));

