I have a InputSupplier&lt;FileInputStream> which I want to pass along to a consumer of the supplier.  However, I'd like to wrap the input streams in GZIPInputStream's.  It would be nice to have a method to transform my InputSupplier&lt;InputStream> into another InputSupplier&lt;InputStream> which can wrap any stream in a given type of FilterInputStream.

Here's some example code I'm using.

```
public class FilterInputStreamSupplier<T extends FilterInputStream> implements InputSupplier<T>
{

    private final InputSupplier<? extends InputStream> fSupplier;
    private final Constructor<T> fConstructor;

    public FilterInputStreamSupplier(InputSupplier<? extends InputStream> supplier, Class<T> clazz)
    {
        fSupplier = supplier;
        try
        {
            fConstructor = clazz.getConstructor(InputStream.class);
        }
        catch (Exception e)
        {
            throw Throwables.propagate(e);
        }
    }

    public static <T extends FilterInputStream> FilterInputStreamSupplier<T>
    of(InputSupplier<? extends InputStream> supplier, Class<T> clazz)
    {
        return new FilterInputStreamSupplier<T>(supplier, clazz);
    }

    @Override
    public T getInput() throws IOException
    {
        InputStream in = fSupplier.getInput();
        try
        {
            return fConstructor.newInstance(in);
        }
        catch (Exception e)
        {
            throw Throwables.propagate(e);
        }
    }    

}
```

Which I use as follows:

```
InputSupplier<GZIPInputStream> gzipSupplier = FilterInputStreamSupplier.of(fileSupplier, GZIPInputStream.class);
```

Is this too special purpose?  Looks like it would also cover some of Issue 425.

